'''Rupert and Buckley''' is a British University derived clothing brand with its brand headquartered in [[Barnstaple, Devon]].<ref name="insider">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/south-west/113338-crowdfunders-sought-upmarket-bath-fashion-retailer |title=Insider News South West – Crowdfunders sought for upmarket fashion label |work=Insidermedia.com |date=2014-04-28 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> The brand creates British-inspired clothing and is most notable for its varsity socks.<ref name="socks">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswest.co.uk/blog/2014/07/09/interview-with-rupert-buckley-founder-and-entrepreneur-james-buckley-thorpe|title=Socks}}</ref>

== History ==

The company was founded in 2011 by [[James Buckley Thorp]] whilst at the [[University of Kent]] where he was reading [[Law]].<ref name="canterbury">{{cite web|url=http://www.canterburytimes.co.uk/shirt-James-designer/story-13819077-detail/story.html |title=Put your shirt on James to be a top designer |work=Canterbury Times |date=2011-11-11 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

Having previously sold items in other outlets, the company opened its first own shop in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]].<ref name="insider" /> In November 2013 the fashion label launched its "Brand Ambassador Scheme".<ref name="mens">{{cite web|last=Taylor |first=Rachael |url=http://www.menswearinsight.com/article-4258-rupert-amp-buckley-grows-with-student-ambassadors/ |title=Rupert & Buckley grows with student ambassadors |work=Menswearinsight.com |date=2013-10-28 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

In early 2014, 25% of the company was sold to private investor Nigel Robinson.<ref name="insider" />

On 5 November 2016, Rupert and Buckley opened their new store in the city centre of Oxford. The opening was supported by rising BBC Introducing star Chris Smee.

On 12 February 2017, founder, [[James Buckley Thorp]], appointed a new CEO. Mr Alexander Newman is the current CEO of Rupert and Buckley LTD.

As part of the brand's expansion plans, they had stores in Durham and Chester.

== Branding and Products ==
The brand name was a combination of the founder's surname and the name he'd like to call his first child.<ref name="wor"/> The company incorporated aspects of British heritage and sporting design in its products,<ref name="insider" /> and used a deep purple and dark yellow colour scheme for its packaging and some of its products.<ref name="wor">{{cite web|url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/business/10110369.Fashion_house_re_locates_to_a_county_farm/ |title=Fashion house re-locates to a county farm |work=[[Worcester News]] |date=2012-12-14 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> The fashion label described itself as grass roots university derived styling and the image and style of the branding was for the university market.<ref name="mens" />

Rupert and Buckley's clothing ranges included rugby shirts, blazers, T-shirts, shirts, chinos and socks.<ref name="insider" /><ref name="bath">{{cite web|url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/Rupert-Buckley-fashion-house-founder-returns-Bath/story-19979606-detail/story.html |title=Rupert and Buckley fashion house founder returns to Bath |work=[[Bath Chronicle]] |date=2013-10-27 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>

